As Americans We
Believe
That God created man for Himself.
That the rights to life, freedom and the pursuit of happiness belong equally
and inalienably to all men because they come from God.
That in making man in His image and likeness with an intellect and will,
He made him essentially different from the animal.
That man's intellect is made for objective, changeless truth, and his will to
choose the right thing according to his conscience.
That man's spiritual, immortal soul binds him in conscience to obligations
in justice and charity to other men.
That there is no freedom without morality, no morality without religion, and
no religion without God.
That these1 changeless truths are certain and thus necessary for happiness in
this life and the next.
Therefore we also believe.
That God and men have a claim to our faith and loyalty.
i
That God is integrated into life only through prayer.
That happiness is spiritual, and not to be confused with pleasure.
That life is based on changeless principle and not on feelings and expediency.
That all education is self education, and therefore takes work and time and
thinking things through. This consists in developing habits and attitudes
which grow through failure as well as success. It involves instilling deep
conviction, strong desires, and courage for action . . . changing the whole
man.
That only heroic men will save the world: men with a sense of direction; a
sense of responsibility; a sense of mission in this life ... a sense of God.
That there are three elements of success in any way of life: a goal; a pro
gram to attain that goal; a dedication to that goal.
That great things are accomplished only by dedicated people, those who offer
themselves completely and forever to a Cause and a Person worthy of
their life and death.
That a reverence and respect for the dignity of others will necessarily make
us conscious of the needs of others for kindness and love.
That what a person is through self-control and self-sacrifice counts more
han what he has in material possessions.
That we can change the world, if we have the courage and maturity to be dif
ferent enough to take God and life seriously.
That Communism, which is diametrically opposed to these truths, can be
defeated only by Americans convinced of and dedicated to these same
truths.
We say to you, fellow Americans, that when America
has put this Creed into its homes and schools, then
can we say "This is the America in which we believe".

Dr. Anthony Bouscaren
Dr. Anthony Bouscaren is a member of the
Institute for American Strategy and the Inter
collegiate Society of Individualists. He also
serves as a Major in the U. S. Marine Corps
Reserve. From 1957-1959 Dr. Bouscaren
was a Consultant to the House Committee on
Un-American Activities.
Dr. Bouscaren holds degrees from Yale
University and the University of California. He
has served on theaculty of the University of
San Francisco (1946-1953); Marquette Uni
versity (1954-1957; The National War Col
lege. Washington. D. C (1957-1959). In
September, 1959. Dr. Bouscaren joined the
faculty of LeMoyne College in Syracuse, New
York where he served as a Professor of Political
Science.

drafted him again as its chief counsel, a posi

Dr. Morris drew upon his long experience
with the subversive Communist inside and out
side the government to author the stimulating
NO WONDER WE ARE LOSING.

University of Dallas, a position which he holds
today.
